result.execSummary:
The defendant Joseph J Kuehn was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property-Special Facts, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Substance Abuse Program.

miscConds.notes: If probation or extended supervision is revoked or will discharge with outstanding financial obligations due, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due.

Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety; defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol, controlled substances, or paraphernalia without a valid prescription; the only exception is that the defendant shall take medications as prescribed; defendant shall submit to random drug and alcohol testing to determine compliance. Defendant shall not associate with, or contact known drug users or dealers and shall have no contact with any place where illegal drugs are purchased, used, kept, stored, packaged or distributed. Defendant shall not possess, buy, sell, trade, borrow or manufacture any firearms or weapons. Defendant shall pay Department of Corrections supervision fees.

Defendant shall participate in all counseling and/or treatment programs directed by the probation agent, including AODA and psychological assessment/treatment and follow through with recommendations including medications prescribed. Defendant shall notify his probation agent within 48 hours of any new prescriptions and changes in medication. Defendant shall inform all medical providers, or anyone administering medical care of his addiction history. Defendant shall designate one specific pharmacy for all prescribed medications.  Defendant shall, within three (3) days, contact the Washington County Jail for purposes of supplying a biological specimen for DNA analysis.  Defendant has the right to request expungement of DNA analysis in writing through the Department of Justice.

timeConds.notes: With Huber privileges consistent with the rules of the jail while the inmate maintains a minimum security status. The defendant, at the discretion of the Sheriff, may perform community service work as an inmate worker in the county jail and shall earn statutory good time for same.
